{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658806"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:56:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:56:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20826"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20826"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13701"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101023"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13701"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20826"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83450"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4088"},{"type":"tags","id":"4173"},{"type":"tags","id":"4738"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5367"},{"type":"tags","id":"11990"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32994"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34716"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34719"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101023"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a repeat pill prescription. She has a history of dysmenorrhea and menorrhagia which have both improved since starting the oral contraceptive pill. She has no other significant medical history and takes mefenamic acid as needed for breakthrough pain. Her menstrual withdrawal bleeds while on the pill are light. She has never been pregnant. Her only sexual partner is her husband. Her last cervical screening test was five years ago, which was normal. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A pelvic ultrasound performed two years ago was unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bimanual examination","Transvaginal ultrasound","Refer for gynaecological assessment","Cervical screening test","Urinary chlamydia NAAT"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights the evidence-based approach to cervical screening in asymptomatic women. The patient\u0027s last cervical screening test was five years ago, making her due for routine screening. She has no active gynaecological symptoms that would warrant additional examination or investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical screening test with speculum examination\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate approach. The cervical screening test can be adequately performed using only a speculum examination to visualise the cervix. There is no evidence that routine pelvic examination improves the sensitivity or specificity of cervical screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBimanual examination\u003C/strong\u003E represents overservicing in asymptomatic women. Routine pelvic examination during cervical screening does not improve cancer detection rates and may cause unnecessary discomfort and anxiety.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransvaginal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as there are no current symptoms or clinical indications that would warrant pelvic imaging. While the patient has a history of dysmenorrhea, it is well-controlled on the oral contraceptive pill, and ultrasound should be reserved for investigation of specific active gynaecological symptoms or concerns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefer for gynaecological assessment\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for a woman with well-controlled dysmenorrhea and no current gynaecological symptoms. She is however due for routine cervical screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrinary chlamydia NAAT\u003C/strong\u003E testing is not routinely indicated. However, it can be offered opportunistically as part of an asymptomatic STI check, particularly given the patient is due a CST, which is the priority in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Routine pelvic examination is not required when performing cervical screening in asymptomatic women.","Pelvic examination should be reserved for investigation of specific gynaecological symptoms.","The sensitivity of cervical screening is not improved by concurrent pelvic examination."],"references":["Choosing wisely [Internet]. [cited 2025 Mar 31]. Don\u2019t routinely do a pelvic examination with a Pap smear. Available from: https://www.choosingwisely.org.au/recommendations/racgp8","Cervical Screening Test options. Cancer Council. https://www.cancervic.org.au/cancer-information/screening/cervical-screening/self-collection"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83450"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20826"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83450"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-29T16:31:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-05T14:39:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13701"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101023"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"att